ðŸ”¹ What is Terraform State?

Terraform uses a state file to track every resource it creates.
Itâ€™s basically Terraformâ€™s memory.
If the state is lost or corrupted, Terraform wonâ€™t know what exists in your cloud.

ðŸ”¹ Why Remote Backend?

Keeping the state file on your local system is risky.
A remote backend (like AWS S3) lets you:

Store the state safely

Share it with your team

Avoid issues like conflicting local state copies

Example backend (S3):

terraform {
  backend "s3" {
    bucket = "your-bucket-name"
    key    = "terraform/statefile.tfstate"
    region = "ap-south-1"
  }
}

ðŸ”¹ Why Use DynamoDB for Locking?

When multiple people run Terraform at the same time, the state can get corrupted.
DynamoDB locking prevents that.

It ensures only one Terraform operation can modify the state at a time.

DynamoDB lock table example:

resource "aws_dynamodb_table" "terraform_locks" {
  name         = "terraform-locks"
  billing_mode = "PAY_PER_REQUEST"
  hash_key     = "LockID"

  attribute {
    name = "LockID"
    type = "S"
  }
}


Then add locking to your backend:

backend "s3" {
  bucket         = "your-bucket-name"
  key            = "terraform/statefile.tfstate"
  region         = "ap-south-1"
  dynamodb_table = "terraform-locks"
}

ðŸ”¹ Why This Setup Matters

Prevents state corruption

Makes Terraform safe for teams

Adds reliability and consistency

Helps manage infra in a clean, professional way
